The error C2760 typically indicates that there is a problem with the template instantiation. One possible solution to this error is to make sure that the template parameter is a type that can be used in a constant expression. To achieve this, we can add the "constexpr" specifier to the template declaration. Here is the revised code:

template <typename T>
constexpr void loadFromJson(const nlohmann::json& j, const std::string& key, T& var)
{
    if ( j.contains(key) && j[key].is<T>()) 
    {
        var = j[key].get<T>();
    }
}

Note that this solution assumes that the error is caused by a non-constant expression being used as a template parameter. If the error is due to some other cause, additional changes may be needed to the code.

The error C2670 indicates that the binary operator "&&" cannot be applied to the types involved in the expression. This error message suggests that one or both of the operands are not of appropriate type for the operation.

One possible solution to this error is to use the "std::enable_if" template in conjunction with the "std::is_same" type trait to constrain the types that the template function can accept. Here is the revised code:

```
#include <type_traits>

template <typename T>
typename std::enable_if<std::is_same_v<T, bool> 
                        || std::is_same_v<T, int> 
                        || std::is_same_v<T, double>,
                        void>::type 
loadFromJson(const nlohmann::json& j, const std::string& key, T& var)
{
    if ( j.contains(key) && j[key].is<T>()) 
    {
        var = j[key].get<T>();
    }
}
```

In the above code, we are using the "enable_if" template to check whether the type T is either bool, int or double. If it is, then the template function will be instantiated. Otherwise, the template function will be removed from the overload set and will not be considered.

Note that we are using the "typename" keyword before the "std::enable_if" to indicate that it refers to a type within a template argument list.

With the above changes, the error C2670 should be resolved.

